## Step 1: Enable GitHub Pages ### Theory: What is GitHub Pages? GitHub Pages lets you turn your repository into a website. This is a great way to share your project, resume, portfolio, documentation, or even a blog with the world. When you enable GitHub Pages on a repository, GitHub takes the content that's on the main branch and publishes a website based on its contents. > [!NOTE] > Learn more in the [GitHub Pages documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/pages/getting-started-with-github-pages/about-github-pages). ### Activity: Enable GitHub Pages 1. With GitHub Pages enabled Mona will be preparing the next step in this exercise!

issue.title: Parsing for Georgian
issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

I'm currently using Lute to learn Georgian. I've been learning it on and off over some time now and I recently just started building my vocab base from scratch, meaning I've added a few specific texts aimed at students and been going through to mark words as known or highlighted red (these will eventually become anki cards). Georgian, however, is an agglutinative language, so any time I come across an inflected noun it takes a couple clicks to add a new parent term (the nominative) or connect it to an existing one. This over time adds up to a lot of minutes spent on "cleaning" any given text. I won't even get into the verbal system.

**Describe the solution you'd like**

I'm aware that Turkish has parsing to handle its own agglutination. Is it feasable to add parsing as well for Georgian in Lute?

comment.body:
Hi @trabaxaduri, apologies for the late reply.  Thanks for the note.

Turkish doesn't have a complex parser, it only has a small hook to handle the weird letter "i" (ref [this reddit post](https://www.reddit.com/r/turkishlearning/comments/1c7quon/can_someone_explain_the_difference_between_i_and/)) which was an issue for capitalization.  So strange.

Right, cleaning an existing text can be a drag.  One thing I did with Spanish was just go through and mark terms, but not create parents.  Then, eventually, I'd do a "bulk parent assign" from the term listing page, or occasionally from the reading pane.  See the manual, https://luteorg.github.io/lute-manual/usage/terms/bulk-editing.html .  It's not a _frictionless_ solution, but it might be ok.

Some Korean learners use Lute, and that has similar challenges.  I'm not sure how they're managing though!

Beyond this, I'm not sure what to do.  Maybe a subsequent processing step, using something like spaCy (a language parsing tool), to map terms, using a bulk term import?  ????   It's challenging, and I don't know if Georgian even has a model.

issue.title: [WIP] URGENT: Fix Survey & Game, Repair DB Schema/Migrations, and Polish UI (Luxury, Elegant, Sophisticated, Mobile-First)
issue.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> @copilot
> 
> 
> 
> Summary
> 
> The NOEMI Survey App needs a full sync to the updated docs/noemi-survey-config.json, a UI polish pass to meet brand requirements (luxury, elegance, sophistication, mobile-first), a working tutorial flow in the swipe game, and database repairs: several .sql files do not run cleanly, and the runtime schema is out of sync with the apps expectations. Update tests accordingly.
> 
> 
> 
> Goals
> 		Render exactly what the updated JSON specifies (survey + game tutorial).
> 		Make the survey UI consistent, refined, and mobile-first.
> 		Ensure all migrations run safely on a fresh Supabase DB.
> 		Bring live schema into alignment with supabase/expected-schema.sql.
> 		Update unit/E2E tests to reflect the new copy and flows.
> 
> 
> 
> Scope of Work (Checklists)
> 
> 1) Survey UI & Copy
> 		Sync all copy to docs/noemi-survey-config.json.
> 		Replace How do you identify?  What is your gender?.
> 		Remove ritual language across title, subtitle, prompts, options.
> 		Ensure app uses JSON as source-of-truth (no stale strings in code).
> 		Tighten spacing & type scale (mobile-first) in src/index.css.
> 		Reduce headline sizes (h1, .group-title) using clamp(...).
> 		Use tighter vertical rhythm: prefer var(--space-2|3) within question blocks and --space-4 between blocks.
> 		Keep lines at ~6575ch width where applicable; maintain max-width caps.
> 		Standardize input widths (notably Q1) via reusable classes in src/index.css:
> 		.survey-input, .survey-select, .survey-textarea  width: 100%, max-width: 560px, box-sizing: border-box.
> 		Apply to all inputs/selects/textareas in src/components/Survey.jsx.
> 		Eliminate fragile selectors that cause style bleed:
> 		Replace .survey-wrapper .stack:first-child with a named container class (e.g., .progress-summary) and update markup in Survey.jsx.
> 		Modularize question rendering in Survey.jsx:
> 		Extract SingleSelectQuestion, MultiSelectQuestion, ScaleQuestion, etc., for consistency and easier styling.
> 		Welcome screen cleanup in src/components/App.jsx:
> 		Ensure survey.meta.title, subtitle, and CTA reflect JSON.
> 		Remove mystical ritual phrasing.
> 		A11y:
> 		Every control has a <label htmlFor>.
> 		Focus rings visible and tasteful.
> 		Click/tap targets  40px.
> 
> Acceptance (UI):
> 		Headings reduced and consistent.
> 		No styling bleed from :first-child.
> 		Inputs full-width on mobile; capped on larger screens.
> 		All copy reflects JSON updates.
> 		Axe audit has no new violations.
> 
> 
> 
> 2) Swipe Game & Tutorial
> 		Tutorial cards: read tutorial sequence defined at the bottom of docs/noemi-survey-config.json and present it before the game starts.
> 		Replace the hard-coded sequence in src/hooks/useSwipeGame.js with JSON-driven content.
> 		Support Next / Start CTAs.
> 		Persist tutorial state:
> 		Store a tutorial seen flag in localStorage.
> 		Add View tutorial link within game UI to replay.
> 		Game polish:
> 		Align button and deck spacing with tightened tokens.
> 		Confirm arrow keys map correctly (Right=Like, Left=Dislike, Up=Love, Down=Unsure).
> 		Maintain focus management after swipe.
> 		Copy cleanup:
> 		Remove ritual language from tooltips, headings, helper text.
> 
> Acceptance (Game):
> 		JSON tutorial displays on first run, can be replayed, and is skippable.
> 		Keyboard and touch swipes work; instant visual feedback remains.
> 		Game UI respects new spacing and type scale.
> 
> 
> 
> 3) Database & SQL (Supabase / Postgres)
> 
> Problem: Some .sql files fail; app expects tables/columns/policies that may not exist or differ in production. Must repair with safe, additive migrations.
> 		BEST TO DELETE EVERYTHING AND START FROM SCRATCH (DROP ALL TABLES AND BEGIN FRESH WITH NEW SUPABASE DEPLOY INSTRUCTIONS)
> 		Save the report as a GitHub Actions artifact and paste a summary in this issue.
> 		If no DB URL is supplied, at least validate expected schema syntax (script supports this).
> 		Migrations must apply cleanly on a fresh DB:
> 		supabase/migrations/0001_init.sql (baseline)
> 		supabase/migrations/0002_add_design_tables.sql (design tables, safe column adds, indexes, RLS)
> 		supabase/migrations/0003_fix_participants_rls_policies.sql (RLS fixes for participants and swipes)
> 		If any fail, add new NNNN_description.sql migrations that only use:
> 		CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS
> 		ALTER TABLE  ADD COLUMN with existence checks
> 		CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS
> 		DROP POLICY IF EXISTS + CREATE POLICY
> 		No destructive operations; never drop/alter types on live data without a dedicated migration plan & manual approval.
> 		Align to supabase/expected-schema.sql:
> 		Ensure participants includes: email, marketing_opt_in, answers jsonb, location_data jsonb, is_complete boolean, progress text, created_at, updated_at.
> 		Ensure design_sets, designs, swipes exist with required indexes and RLS.
> 		RLS policies:
> 		anon can INSERT into participants and swipes and SELECT them for analytics.
> 		anon can SELECT design_sets and designs.
> 		authenticated has full access for admin operations.
> 		Verify with a policy existence check (see 0003 approach); add verification DO $$ blocks if needed.
> 		Seeds / static content:
> 		Confirm /public/designs/index.json exists and is current.
> 		Confirm any generator script (e.g., scripts/split_quadrants.py) outputs the structure the game expects.
> 		DB health banner (src/components/DbHealthBanner.jsx):
> 		Ensure checkDbHealth validates new tables and surfaces helpful diagnostics.
> 		Improve copy and add a copy diagnostics success state.
> 
> Acceptance (DB):
> 		Fresh Supabase DB applies all migrations without error.
> 		check-schema-drift.sh reports no drift against expected-schema.sql.
> 		Anonymous survey submissions and swipes work end-to-end.
> 		Policies verified present; CI job captures a drift report artifact.
> 
> 
> 
> 4) Tests
> 		Unit / component (Vitest + RTL):
> 		Update label queries to match new copy (e.g., Gender question).
> 		Ensure each question type has a rendering & interaction test.
> 		Add tests that ensure no styling bleed (first option unaffected).
> 		E2E (Playwright):
> 		Welcome  Survey  Game happy path.
> 		Tutorial appears on first play, can be skipped/replayed.
> 		Keyboard and swipe inputs recorded to Supabase (mock if needed).
> 		Visual expectations for spacing/headings at mobile widths.
> 		DB validations (mocked):
> 		Test schema drift script wrapper or a small Node wrapper that asserts non-empty diff triggers a failure state in CI.
> 		Snapshots / visual:
> 		Re-record when UI changes are intentional.
> 		Add minimal visual checks for type scale and spacing changes.
> 
> Acceptance (Tests):
> 		All tests green locally and in CI.
> 		Coverage includes at least one flow per question type and the tutorial path.
> 
> 
> 
> 5) Misc Codebase Hygiene
> 		Services & utils: Review supabaseClient.js, analytics.js, geolocation.js for robust error handling and logging.
> 		Docs:
> 		README.md: update usage, dev modes (?dev=true, ?play=true), tutorial mention.
> 		AGENTS.md: reflect modular components and CSS token usage.
> 		Add comments to docs/noemi-survey-config.json describing fields and constraints.
> 		Env & examples:
> 		Add .env.example with VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, and any required flags.
> 		Add a quickstart section for local DB testing with Supabase CLI.
> 		CI pipeline:
> 		Ensure CI runs: pnpm install, pnpm lint, pnpm test, pnpm test:e2e, pnpm build, scripts/check-schema-drift.sh.
> 		Upload schema drift report as artifact on failure.
> 		Perf & a11y:
> 		Image preloading in the game is already implemented; validate that it doesnt block input.
> 		Recheck keyboard nav and screen reader labels across survey and game.
> 
> 
> 
> How to Reproduce (Current Issues)
> 	1.	Copy mismatch: Launch app and observe any text not matching docs/noemi-survey-config.json (gender prompt, ritual wording).
> 	2.	Style bleed: Inspect first items in answer lists; confirm no unintended styles caused by :first-child.
> 	3.	Input widths: Q1 sub-questions should not have inconsistent widths on mobile and desktop.
> 	4.	Tutorial: Game should show JSON-driven tutorial; currently the sequence may be hard-coded in useSwipeGame.js.
> 	5.	DB failures: Apply migrations to a fresh Supabase instance; note any errors or missing policies/tables.
> 
> 
> 
> Proposed Implementation Notes
> 		Keep all database changes non-destructive; if breaking changes are required, open a separate PR with a data-safe plan.
> 		Encapsulate styles using CSS custom properties and named classes; avoid global selectors that target structural positions.
> 		Read tutorial config from JSON, not code, to prevent drift.
> 		Put all copy behind JSON to avoid stale strings in JSX.
> 
> 
> 
> Commands
> 
> # Install & run
> pnpm install
> pnpm dev
> 
> # Lint / typecheck / tests
> pnpm lint
> pnpm test
> pnpm test:e2e
> pnpm build
> 
> # Supabase / schema checks (requires SUPABASE_DB_URL or DATABASE_URL)
> ./scripts/check-schema-drift.sh
> 
> # (Dev-only) Reset DB
> # supabase db reset
> 
> 
> 
> 
> Definition of Done
> 		No copy mismatches; all text is JSON-driven.
> 		UI spacing/type standardized; inputs consistent; no style bleed.
> 		Tutorial is JSON-driven, persists seen state, and is replayable.
> 		All migrations apply cleanly; schema drift check passes.
> 		Unit/E2E tests updated and passing; CI green.
> 
> 
> 
> If anything blocks progress (e.g., missing Supabase credentials), post diagnostics in this issue and PR and proceed with mocked paths where possible.


Fixes #76.

issue.title: Issue running MoSe2_AA_1108.pth with LAMMPS Allegro
issue.body:
Dear Professor Liu,

I am very interested in DPmoire, and I really appreciate that you provided this model
I tried testing with the provided `MoSe2_AA_1108.pth` model. After following the README instructions to install LAMMPS with Allegro, I first encountered an error saying that allegro3232 could not be found.

I then switched to a more general command:
```
pair_style      allegro
pair_coeff      * * MoSe2_AA_1108.pth Mo Se
```
However, this led to the following error message:
```
NequIP/Allegro is using input precision d and output precision d
Exception: Only accepts model paths with extension `.nequip.pth` or `.nequip.pt2`, but found MoSe2_AA_1108.pth
```
It seems that `MoSe2_AA_1108.pth` is not in the standard format expected by Allegro, and therefore LAMMPS cannot run with it.

Could you please provide a more detailed installation guide for LAMMPS with pair_allegro, especially regarding the required versions of the libraries (PyTorch, NequIP, Allegro, etc.) that are compatible with the model file?

Alternatively, would it be possible for you to provide a script (or instructions) to convert `MoSe2_AA_1108.pth` into the standard format that the latest version of Allegro can recognize and execute?

Thank you very much for your help!

Best regards,
Yiming Ma

comment.body:
Dear Yiming Ma,

Thank you very much for your interest in DPmoire and your detailed feedback. 

The error you observed may be caused by incompatible version of pair_allegro. Our models are trained and deployed with `nequip==0.5.6`, `allegro==0.2.0`, which is not supported by pair_allegro v0.7.0 as they mentioned [here](https://github.com/mir-group/pair_nequip_allegro/releases/tag/v0.7.0). 

pair_allegro v0.6.0 should works well with our models.

Best regards, 
Jiaxuan Liu

commits.message:
improve VMAF & small refactor (#1074)

A user reported a problem where they couldn't use NEG and UHD features
combined.
I could reproduce it and added the fix along with some improvements:

- Centralizes VMAF model selection logic into a single function instead
of duplicating the same conditional logic across multiple places.
- Eliminates hardcoded model name checks by replacing exact string
matching with simple detection
- Makes VMAF model selection consistent across all functions by ensuring
the same feature-based logic is used everywhere
- Fixes inconsistent default model behavior where some cases used no
model while others used hardcoded models
- Removes code duplication by replacing repeated match statements for
model selection with a single reusable function
- Prepares the codebase for dynamic VMAF feature configuration by
threading the feature parameters through the entire call chain

Add score-based enhanced extra splits method

The goal of this change is to improve the locations chosen for extra
splits, rather than being exactly in the middle, to being weighted based
on a combination of scenecut cost and distance from the middle.

Closes #1035

Revert "Add score-based enhanced extra splits method"

This reverts commit b93662c80ab2a332316e039d90cd75b41cf57b16.

Add score-based enhanced extra splits method

The goal of this change is to improve the locations chosen for extra
splits, rather than being exactly in the middle, to being weighted based
on a combination of scenecut cost and distance from the middle.

Closes #1035
Handle importing old scenes files format

Migrate encode tests to integration tests (#1085)

This improves organization and makes it easier to run encode tests
locally, and has the added benefit of including encode tests in the test
coverage numbers.

Remove tokio dependency

We were not particularly using tokio's features in any way that couldn't
be satified by basic threads, nor do we have anywhere near the level of
concurrency which would result in benefitting from an async
architecture, so we can remove this rather heavy dependency from the
codebase, which reduced the time to compile a full release build by
about 10%.

Remove parking_lot dependency

As of Rust 1.62 the `std::sync::Mutex` was refactored to make its
performance comparable to `parking_lot::Mutex`, which means there's no
need for us to import this additional dependency anymore.

This also found and fixed and issue where we were creating a lock twice
for every line of stderr parsing, which should reduce performance
overhead.

Fix: Absolut Path generation on Linux when using dgdecnv (#1089)

Hi,

this small PR fixes an issue, that occurs when using dgdecnv on a linux
system (Arch Linux 6.15.5-arch1-1 in my case). When starting av1an like
this `av1an -i test.mkv -o output.mkv -m dgdecnv`, av1an crashes with a
file not found error:

> Error: No such file or directory (os error 2)

After checking av1an with strace -f, I could see that av1an was trying
to access the temp directory at a point in time, when it was not created
yet.

Stepping through the code, I could pin point it to the
`to_absolute_path` method, that uses `path.canonicalize()` under linux.
This method does not seem to work on files (or directories) that are
non-existant. Unfortunately, `to_absolut_path` is called in
`vapoursynth.rs` for dgdecnv before the temp directories have been
created.

Instead of changing the order of initialization i just removed the
inline function and changed the code to use `absolute(path)` for all
operating systems. This function seems to work just fine under linux.

Changes to scenechange decoding

- Use the `VapoursynthDecoder` when the user provides a vpy script
- Otherwise, use ffmpeg, as it is faster. We can perform downscaling and pixel format conversion with ffmpeg.
- Fix `sc_pix_format` when user provides Vapoursynth input, as previously this argument was not working for that scenario
- Add integration tests for sc-downscale and sc-pix-format functionality and for vpy input

The result is that we are always using the fastest available method for any given scenario.

Add more pedantic clippy lints

The most significant change is disallowing `.unwrap()`. Instead, we
should:

- If the error is one that we never expect to occur in production (i.e.
  it indicates a bug), we should use `.expect` to add reasoning why we
  believe this won't occur.
- If the error is expected to be triggerable in production, we should
  bubble it up with `?` instead of using `.unwrap()`. Unwrap in
  production is bad for a variety of reasons, so we should avoid it.

There are also a number of lints to improve code readability, use more
idiomatic patterns, and improve performance. The reason some of these
lints are opt-in is because they are restrictions that may not apply to
all code bases. There are a few where we are only going to enable them
for the core library and not for the CLI, for example. Some others are
still experimental and may have false positives. Instances of false
positives can be ignored using `#[expect(clippy::lint_name, reason =
"...")]`.

The following Target Quality options are now supported by Zones:

* `--target-quality`
* `--target-metric`

* `--probes`
* `--probing-rate`
* `--probe-res`

parsing)

`--probe-video-params copy` or `--probe-video-params "--preset 6
--keyint 0 --film-grain 0 --psy-rd 0 --spy-rd 0"` instead. Supplying
`copy` will copy the params from `-v --video-params`. For probe video
parameters, it is recommended to use a faster speed/preset/cpu-used than
the encoder parameters and to omit or adjust parameters that reduce
probing accuracy such as `--film-grain` or `--psy-rd`.

- Changes the default chunk method to `BestSource`. The filter is much
  faster than it used to be, now being equivalent to `ffms2` with the
  exception of the slow indexing pass, which only needs to be done once
  per input. This filter is now widely recommended as a sane default
  around the Vapoursynth community, so it seems sane to make this our
  default now as well.
- Use the same Vapoursynth source filter for scene detection that we use
  for chunking. This at least ensures consistent decoding even if there
